It’s 12:42 on a Wednesday afternoon. I’m sitting at my favorite cafe, having a cup of coffee, when the realization strikes: it’s almost the end of the year.

Just like in past years, I have no idea where the time has gone. Are we really living if we don’t remember the days? Maybe it’s my bad memory, but I have no recollection of last week. Is this what people think about during their final moments when they talk about their regrets? Ticking off to-do lists and goals, moving from day to night in a routine that feels almost robotic. Worrying about things that won’t matter in a few months. Only to find themselves years later, having lived a life they never really lived. 

Don’t worry, the point of this caption isn’t to dampen your spirits but rather the opposite—at least, I hope. I hope we realize that life is in the small joys hidden in plain sight, easily overlooked in the rush. It’s about a random smile from a stranger, a text from a friend you haven’t spoken to in a while, or just an afternoon spent at your favorite cafe, having a cup of coffee.
